Teleporters.

A teleporter relocates the player from one spot on the map to another the instant they land on it. In its simplest form it's a fixed pad: step onto the tile and you're whisked to a destination elsewhere on the same map. But a teleporter can also hunt — it can watch for the player to come within range and then creep toward them, so the pad chases you down and teleports you when it catches up. That makes it equally useful as a convenient shortcut and as a menacing trap you have to outrun.

A teleporter moves the player within the current map. To send the player to a different map entirely, use a travelpoint instead; to move the player up and down between heights, use a lift or an elevator.

How a teleporter works.

A teleporter sits at a starting tile and plays a continuous loop sound there so the player can hear it. It has a seeing range on each axis — how close the player must come before the teleporter notices them. Once the player is within that range on every axis, the teleporter is alerted, and from then on, every speed interval, it takes one step toward the player along whichever axes you've allowed it to move on. When the teleporter and the player end up on the same tile, the player is instantly moved to the teleporter's finishing coordinates, a move sound plays, and — if the teleporter is single use — the pad is spent and disappears.

This gives two very different entities from the same fields:

A still teleporter, with no movement axes enabled, is a classic pad. It never moves; the player has to walk onto its tile deliberately, and doing so teleports them. The seeing range doesn't matter much for a still pad since the player reaches it by stepping on it.
A hunting teleporter, with one or more movement axes enabled, homes in. The moment the player strays within its seeing range it starts closing the distance along the chosen axes, and it teleports them as soon as it reaches them. A wide seeing range makes it alert from across the map; a narrow one only wakes it when the player is close.

Teleporter fields.

The teleporter form takes the following:

Starting position. The starting x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile the teleporter sits on.
Finishing position. The finishing x and y (and z on 3d maps) — where the player is sent when caught.

X seeing range. How far along the x axis the teleporter can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full width.
Y seeing range. How far along the y axis the teleporter can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full depth.
Z seeing range. On 3d maps, how far along the height axis the teleporter can notice the player. Defaults to the map's full height.

Speed. Milliseconds between each step the teleporter takes toward the player once it has noticed them — smaller is a faster, more aggressive chase.

Teleporter sound (a folder name from the teleporter sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies a loop clip (the ambient hum at the pad) and a move clip (played at the moment of teleport). Pick none for a silent teleporter.

Move on x axis (checkbox). Whether the teleporter may chase the player along the x axis once it has noticed them.
Move on y axis (checkbox). Whether the teleporter may chase the player along the y axis once it has noticed them.
Move on z axis (checkbox). Whether the teleporter may chase the player along the z axis once it has noticed them; this option only appears on 3d maps.

Leave all the move axes unchecked for a fixed pad the player must step onto deliberately; check one or more to turn the teleporter into a hunter that closes in along those axes.

Single use (checkbox). When checked, the teleporter vanishes after teleporting the player once. Leave it unchecked for a pad that keeps working every time.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the teleporter sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the move clip of the highlighted theme and hold control and press L to hear its loop clip.

Authoring teleporters by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a teleporter is: teleporter x y x2 y2 xrange yrange speed teleportertype movex movey singleuse — where x y is the starting tile, x2 y2 the destination, and the ranges are the seeing distances. On 3d maps a z is inserted after each coordinate pair, a z range after the y range, and a move-on-z flag after the move-on-y flag: teleporter x y z x2 y2 z2 xrange yrange zrange speed teleportertype movex movey movez singleuse. The move and single use fields are the literal words true or false, and the teleporter sound must match a teleporter sound folder name or the word none.
